ve a - a box - and put some soil on there and they used to put sweet pea seeds in and grow them up the wall. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 They grew well did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Sometimes. I remember once coming home from school and there was a whole crowd of sweet peas on them - me 
father had put them on there to show - you know, stuck them in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Did you go fishing or walking or bicycling as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well I had a bicycle. But we never used to go far. Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Where would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well just round home. And - I never
 bothered with fishing and I've never interested me. But walking - I used to walk - my cousin and I, we used to go to a neighbour's farm - Coxhead Farm down in Getticker nearly every Saturday. To walk - yes, we used - well we'd no idea - used to go right 
u
p Culverrston Road you know and Comptons Lane and there was a - when you got on - Cromptons Lane, I think' it's Hattons Lane now there, well, from Hattons Lane to Dunbobbin Road used to be a field and there used to be horse polo there. I used to go and wa
tch that as a little boy. I used to go down past - past Showell church and down - down there to a farm - Coxhead Farm, Getticker - it was Capsticks. We used to go for the day on a Saturday. In the fine weather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Who would you have gone with on these walks and bicycling - was there any particular person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
No. Just - no, just friend - no, like - but - well my cousin and I - we - my age. Well he's a fortnight younger than me - we used to be two little lads going off together you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Did you go to any theatres or concerts, music-halls or cinemas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
Well, I used occasionally - if it was a concert perhaps at Dovedale and my sister was in it I used to go and we used to go as I told you to the - the Olympia. The circus every Christmas, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6113540\charrsid5983795 I think was penny. For a pennyw}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
orth of sweet - of sweeties. And you know the far - the petrol pump is - well, the second house up used to be the sweet shop. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Did anyone outside the home help y
our mother look after her house or family? I know you had two living in maids but did any friends or relatives help her at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No, there used to be a - a - latterly a man - a lady named Mrs Jarvis used to come in and - about twice a week - and used 
to help her with the washing when it got too - too much and - and used to go through the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 But when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well - yes, when we were young and then after we got older she s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6113540\charrsid5983795 t}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 ill came up to Hillside for a while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 If your mother was ill or confined to bed how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Two maids, yes, they were all right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Do you remember when one of your younger sisters were born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No. I can't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Yes. Well - fa
ther's brother lived here in - and then was - his cousins - Atkinsons, they - both had farms. My mother hadn't. My mother's of course was up in Scotland.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 All her relatives would be up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Yes, they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 How often did you see your father's relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh, I often used to go to these farms. Myself - 'cos I was interested you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Would they come and visit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh - yes, they used to come round and visit us. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Did your parents have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Where did they see them, did they share the same friends or what kind of friends were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
Well - they used to share the - all the - the same type of friends and that you see. They were - there was - in those days I don't think there was a great lo
t of visiting done. There was - perhaps social evening or a Sunday evening after church or something of that - a sing-song. They used to make your own pleasure. Yes, but other than that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Would they go out a lot, regularly - as much as friends came to see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well I don't think they'd go out often. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 When friends came would they be offered anything to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh Lor' yes, always - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Would you say that the friends invited in were your mother's friends or your father's friends or both of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Both.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 They were mainly mutual friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Both - yes. Definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Can you remember friends calling in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No, occasionally they would call in - yes, occasionally. We never kne
w when they were - if they were coming. 'Course they knew like all of us knew that we'd - it was a dairy and we were busy and - that was it you see. No, no, 'cos most of them were in the same line more or less. Busy - yes, yes. Well of course Dunbobbin Fa
rm was a corner of Dunbobbin Road and Weoolton Road and all that was fi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6113540\charrsid5983795 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 lds, right down to Rutherford Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 You said your parents had sort of musical evenings when they met their friends - would they play any games or would it be mainly music?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No, it was a concert mostly. Yes, a concert.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 But when they had their friends in would they have sung then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh yes - well, yes, used to - well, used to play games amongst themselves, yes. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Many people divide society into different soci
al classes or groups, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another? And could you tell me what the different ones were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well - the only - the only - thing I could remem - take on actually was the social -
 as you know, which goes on now was - from the Catholics and the - the Protestants of the thing you see that - because - but father was never - never against it. - in any shape or form but there - that was there. And also we always - being round here were
 looked as the gentry - as higher you see, because they were all big ship owners and - all that type of thing round here. But in the village - well, they were just - all sorts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 What class would you say you belonged to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh, just the ordinary - medium class. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 What sort of people belonged to this same medium class as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
Well - there was - all - all the - trades people, more or less, from all types of trade because they were nearly all individual trades in those days. Se
e, all those shops were all individual in those days. On the same - bakers were the - Rula Gooney's that used to be the - do you remember that as a bread shop? Used to bake all their own bread there - yes. Well - Greenwood - you know Greenwood - well that
's the grandson. Yes. Yes. H-s mother was a baker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 What sort of people belonged to the other classes - you mentioned the gentry, I suppose you'd call them the higher class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 What sort of other people - for instance the lower classes o
r the working classes - what sort of people would have belonged to those - you mentioned the ship owners and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh well most of the ship owners and timber merchants and all that used to live all round Mossley Hill. They were what - used to look 
up to - because they - most of them used to have anything up to six and seven and eight maids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Living on quite a high standard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh, very high class then. They all used to come with the carriage and pairs - horses - two horses. And here were the 
barracks, was then - it used to be a cab stables. And I can remember - as long as I can remember - the - all the gentry amalgamating there any sporting type with their horses and four in hands and - in the full regalia, going to the National up from Rose 
L
ane through here. From here, yes. About eleven o'clock they used to go for the National. Right up to Aintree and back. And all the Royalty used to come in here - Mossley Hill station you know. Oh yes. King George the V and the whole of the Royal Family us
ed to go out to - to Knowsley to the - stay when the - they laid the foundation stone of the - the Liverpool Cathedral.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 They used to arrive at Mossley Hill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Always, yes. Oh it used to be a great thing here in the old days on the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 You'd see quite a few interesting sights wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
Oh we did. Saw - I saw Edward VII. Yes. I was only little - very little. 'Cos 1907 he died didn't he. Look at the reigns we've lived in. Oh it was - it was what do you call it first. Queen Victoria 
- Edward VLL - George the V, George VI - Edward VII. Yes, it is, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No. A positive no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Were you ever told to touch your cap or show respect in some way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Always. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 To any particular person or to everyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 To your elders - always, yes. I still - I', sorry enough but I still do it. Yes. I know as a little boy we used to have the c}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6113540\charrsid5983795 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 ps, you know, that used to go on the back of your head and I had curly hair and more often than not got hold of my hair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Do you remember anyone you called Sir or Master or Madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Not as a little boy, no. No, I don't think so. I'd say - I daresay I'd say yes sir to a - people, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 But not in particular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh no, no, no. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well the - I - I know the men and the - used to call sometimes the Master but - I think it was just Mr and Mrs Wilson all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 In the district or village here where you lived who were considered the most important people - you've already mentioned there were ship}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6113540\charrsid5983795 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 owners and people round here - would you have classed them as important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh they were, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Anyone else you can think of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
Well we always used to look up to the - the Vicars of the church, you see, there was - there was like four - of them. There was Canon Hertford at Mossley Hill, there was Fleming-Shearer at Dovedale and there was 
Gibson-Smith at Ollerton and Kirk Pike at St Barnabas. 'Course there wasn't St Anthonys then you know - it was up at Bishop Heaton then. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Did you come into contact with these people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 We used to come into contact with the - Fleming-Shear
er. Well we actually we - I've come in contact with a - few of them but - Canon - him being our minister he used to often come and - in and have a chat you see. He was a very homely man. An awfully - Scoth man. He was awfully nice chap. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Can you think of any other people in the district who you would have thought of as important?
