\insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 l was - as of course you can see by the size of the houses. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Who would teachers have been friendly with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well - I can't say as I know really - schoolteachers. I got on very well with my headmaster after a while but I didn't
 go much for him at the time. Mind you he was exceptionally strict. Oh yes. Well they were in those days. 'Course I - I was about nine - eight or nine when I - we went to Dovedale when it was built and we'd a - the man who was the headmaster then was a ma
n
 named Musker and he was choir master and organist at Mossley Hill and he was really mustard. He was. He used to - he had to go in your lines and see the backs of your shoes and your front and your hands and everything else all clean and everything. Oh he
 
was noted for it and he used to use the stick. Wellm- I don't know whether I should tell you this but I - we were once - I was not a very good scholar at school except I was quite above - I think I was above average in - in arithmetic and such as that and
 
this was a - a midsummer exam and you always had to get in one desk you see behind the other and I finished my paper and I happened just to look and I saw the chap - over looking over into my thing and I turned round and there was a Miss Morris then. She 
s
ent us both out. And of course that was an awful offence and we had to touch our toes in this teachers room, I always remember that, and I never let on to me mother but the other boy never came back to school in the afternoon - the two of us together you 
s
ee. So in the evening, it was Friday and it was bath night, and when mother saw my back - I was black and blue from the middle of me back right down to the things. And I can see my father now with his bowler hat on waiting outside the front gate for Muske
r to come down from choir and tell - and - to come in to let him see me. Yes. Oh he had ridged me all right. But -
