\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No. No, they just - just pointed out to him and - and he apol}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9242320\charrsid5983795 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 gi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9242320\charrsid5983795 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 ed to them. I can remember him apologi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9242320\charrsid5983795 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
ing, oh yes. And when I left school - the latter part of my time at school I only went in the morning 'cos they took the war - the war came in you see and I took my father's - had to do - deliver milk of an afternoon with a horse - go right down a
s far as the Liverpool Cathedral. Used to set out at two and get back at half past five. I wasn't - I was - well, I was barely fourteen. Just fourteen actually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Who would the employer's friends have been - your father was an employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 And you felt that the local people were obviously of the same sort of class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
Quite. We were all of the same standard, yes. Yes, amongst the employer groups yes. Mostly amongst our own dairy men and farmers - 'cos the cousins and relation
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 What sort of people would you say went to the same church as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well - in what way do you mean, sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 What kind of people - what were their occupations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh I think of every kind - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Not predominantly one kind more than another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
No, no. No. Actually - the - the church - at Dovedle was Alderman Watts who - were the - the denominated figure you might put it in - the - recreation of the church. I think he - it was his land - he gave the land and I think he'd an awful 
lot to do with the - with - well not on - not so much the running as he - as the building of it. And then there was - well, they were a very nice - quite homely lot and it was a very nice church to go to. Yes, very nice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 What sort of people went to the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 It - it was the Baptist - well actually the - the Baptist is a chapel, they call it - but - yes, that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 You felt your church would have been a Baptist chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh it was a Baptist chapel I should think, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Can you remember any friction between Catholics and Protestants when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 You never personally came into contact with it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No - never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Can you remember any comments that were made about it by people or any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9242320\charrsid5983795 r}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 emark at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
No. I don't think so. We were taught that - by my father which my father was quite a - a good living chap. He was a - he was a - teetotaller but - to mind your own business and also what their - other people did was no concern of yours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Sound advice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 It was. And that - we were - as little ones were to be - seen and not heard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Where you lived id all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or would you say there were different groups?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well - of course in tho
se days you - as a - a boy I didn't look at it as any - that type of thing, you see. But some of them were worse off than us. I'll admit that. But there were others better off than us. But - I think we all got a square meal if we put it that way. There wa
s no - there was no starvation. Oh as far as I know - not in this village anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Do you think that one group felt itself superior to the rest in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well there was - there was the gentry of course they - Mossley Hill area and Ollerton area,
 they were all supposed - well - the aristocrats put it that way. Matter of fact, they used to come here - down to Mossley Hill station and they used to go to town in there - or London and always in the carriage and pair. The horses and that you see. And 
w
here the barracks is now on the hill that used to have about forty horses with - and that. All the gentry used to - oh there was nothing - even the King and Queen and all the Royal family got off at Mossley Hill Station. And of course this time of the yea
r
 was a great time because - they used to regale - all the regalia of the National. With the four in hands. Yes, they used to come from Mossley Hill here. All the gentry used to amalgamate all in full regalia. Yes, they did, about eleven o'clock in the mor
ning they'd set off for - out to Aintree and back again in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Was this group - the gentry as you call them - the only group that felt itself superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh yes. But in the village itself here there was no superiority I don't think. I can't remember of it anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well there was - there were one or two, yes, of the - of the rougher type, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 How would you describe the rougher type - why would they be called the rougher type?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
Well - they - probably didn't - discipline the children like sort of thing as we had and they let go wild or such as that and then of course there was - occasionally where there was drink - and that set in but - 'cos we h
ad two pubs here you know. Yes, there was one here, the Rose and one round the corner in Bridge Road. Yes. That was where the - in Bridge Road - Stanley Terrace was the poorest - and that's where the fun used to be if there was any fun. 'Course I - don't 
remember much of it, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Do you remember a distinction of either rough or respectable between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No, I think quite honestly the labourer and the craftsman got on very, very well together. Yes, there was - 'course we didn't k
now anything of unions in those days You see. The general feeling was they were all men and they did the days work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Yes. Yes, well of course in - in the business y
ou've got to do. Yes, you work together and you - you've got to - take everything as a pinch of salt as the saying is, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No. I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another and can you remember anyone who did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Well - not in those days, I wouldn't - I was too young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 In retrospect - can you think back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No, I don't think so. There was - one or two of them - as the
ir family got older they seemed to - get bit better off and such as that. But - yes, but they were - they were always - we always respected them as - as kiddies and there was no such a thing I don't think as snobbishness. Not in - no, not particular class
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Who would that have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh I daresay you know - of him - Mr George Moon. Do you remember Mr Milne in Elmsley Road? He used to be a little gentleman wit
h a grey beard and you know where the - the little entry used to go through to the bridge - climbing over - in that house there. He was a bachelor. Well he was - he was always a gentleman. And he - he - he was great member of the Mossley Hill church and h
e
 was always to help others. He was a bachelor - he lived with his mother 'til his mother died and then he lived alone with a housekeeper. Yes, he was eighty - I think eighty-five or eighty-six when he died. Oh yes. He used to - I've heard it said, before 
I
 was born, when my - father then lived in Bridge Road where the farm - first farm was I think I've mentioned that, my - I had an uncle who - was an invalid - he had both legs amputated through gangrene. And this Mr Milne used to live on the opposite side 
-
 his back - of the other side of the railway. And they were great friends and were similar of an age and he used to do a lot of painting, my uncle. And I think he wrote a book. Actually I let somebody have it and I've never had it back. The Loss of all th
ings for Ch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9242320\charrsid5983795 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 ist. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Your uncle or Mr Milne.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 My uncle. My father's brother, yes. And he - he died when he was twenty-four in the Northern Hospital. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 You told me you thought Mr Milne was a real gentleman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Oh he was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Can you remember anyone being described as a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
Oh yes, there was a lot of nice gentlemen about. And I got on very well with them but - and special with some - some of the ladies but I couldn't mention - names. Not at the present moment, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Do you remember seeing a policeman around when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 What did you think about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 
Oh - we used to be a bit scared admitted but - he was a nice chappie. He'd - he was a big chap - he was a County police, not Liverpool police. Do
n't forget this wasn't Liverpool. I was born in Lancashire - Mossley Hill, Lancashire. And you know where - Comptons Lane is - not Cromptons Lane - Harthill Road is now - well that used to be an old lane and there was eight cottages there and that was the
 police station where the policemen lived. He used to walk down here into Mossley Hill and back again. He was a big - big fine chap with a great big black beard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1382998 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 When you were naughty did your mother ever say, I'll call a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid418543 RW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14944617\charrsid5983795 No, I don't think - no, I don't think that ever occurred.
